Introductory Data Analysis of US GDP Data¶

DS 220 - Srikar Lanka

Project Information:¶

Dataset Used:¶

This project makes use of a publically available dataset that is available on data.gov. The link to the dataset is here: https://catalog.data.gov/dataset/international-macroeconomic-data-set. The dataset is published by Steven Zahniser of the United States Economic Research Service in the Department of Agriculture. It is a set of GDP Numbers and Growth Rates for every country from 1970 - 2033.

Reason for Choosing Dataset:¶

I choose this datast because I thought it would be interesting to see on paper and visualized trends of the global economics trends. Some trends we are all faimilar with, such as China overtaking the US, the rise of India, etc, but I feel it would also be helpful to take a moment to try and analyze some other trends of the global economy.

I specficially choose this dataset because it was very well organized, had data compiled for regions, and also had Growth Rates.

Key Interested Parties:¶

It is my belief that these data analysis is very helpful and critical for anyone, but more importantly economics and political science majors. Economics is also king at the end of the day, and it is helpful to see any trends that may be occuring that could influence changes in power or growth/decline of a nation. It is through this analysis that key trends can be noted, followed up with, and analyzed, all of which can either influence policy decisions of many governments around the world or simply acknowledge a few of the many trends occuring. Although there are limitless possibilities in what analysis one could do in this field, I will primarily be focusing on general head-to-had analytics as these are what show the historical and future trends that effect our world.

Importat Acknowledgment:¶

By the nature of how the dataset was designed, it is important to notice that this project had to make a slight modification to the datset. The original dataset had the GDP and growth-values all in the same page of the same sheet, and thus I found it would be easier to simply split the dataset into two seperate datasets for the sake of analysis through the course of this project. This dataset is available to the public under Creative Commons Attribution and thus is able to be modified, though it is important that this was stated for any interested parties.

Attribution:¶

This work, "RealGDPValues and GrowthRates", is adapted from "International Macroeconomic Data Set" by Steven Zahniser, now updated by Wendy Zeng and William Johnson used under CC BY 4.0 "RealGDPValues and GrowthRates" is licensed under CC BY 4.0 by Srikar Lanka.

Code Takeaways:¶

From above, we see that we now see a dataset split into two seperate datasets, one called gdpValues which contains the GDP values of countries from 1970 to 2033, and growthRates which contains the Growth Rates of countries from 1971 to 2033.

We also see that it is not just countries that are present, but there are certain groupings such as the World, the World wothout the US, US and Canada, etc. This is something to note as it may present a challenge for certain queries and thus may need to be dealt with.

Part 3: Understanding Basic Data Details¶

Before we conduct analysis and try to answer our questions, we should first get a elementary understanding of the data we are looking. Below we will use various pandas commands that are able to summarize the general trends of note in our data.

Code Explanation and Items of Note:¶

Here, we will make use of the describe() method for both gdpValues and growthRates. This method returns various statistical information such as count, mean, std, min, and max, for each column. In our case, the columns are the years from 1970 to 2033 for GDP Values, and 1971 to 2033 for Growth Rates.

Key Notes for GDP Values: As we see, one interesting thing to note is the ammount of columns grow over-time as possible new organizations and countries start also having values with 211 becoming 232 entries by 2033. Another thing that is interesting to see is how much the mean GDP grows over time with almost a x8 growth. In the same boat, as the economies of certain countries started to take off, we see the standard deviation grow further and further which means we see more countries having GDPs well above the mean (and consquently more countries with GDPs below the mean as-well). It is also very interesting to see the min, 25, 50, 75, and max trends with the min not changing very much as-well-as 25%, 50% and 75% seeing modest gains, and the max just being a completly different scale of number.

Key Notes for Growth Rates: In terms of the addition of new organizations and countries that was expressed above, we see the same trend for Growth Rates, but where growth rates is interesting is how we see a trend of possible economic slowdown. Compared to the start, growth rates are still positive but much lower then they were at the start. The Standard Deviation is also a lot smaller, meaning most countries are all growing in a very similar pace, a theme also reflected in a 25-50-75 marks as the variation between them grows shorter. That being said, there is always a crazy max value every year baring 2025-2033 because they are predictions and things could change, the predicitions have to be more mellow.

Section 2: Data Pre-Processing¶

Now that we have established an elementary understanding of the dataset, we are now able to get going on data analysis. That being said, there is still one critical step that we need to handle in-order to properly be able to do data analysis. That step being pre-processing, a step in-which we fill in any holes in the code and patch any issues that may make data analysis difficult.

Code Explanation and Items of Note:¶

As mentioned above, this dataset contains data for regions as-well-as organizations such as BRICS. This is great data and I will definetly make use of it later, but for the questions I have to start the problem off they will only primarily get in the way. For that reason, I have isolated every row that contains a region or organization and will remove them by passing in an array of these values to the drop method of the dataframe. This will remove these rows and will make for a more simplified data analysis expirience.

Code Explanation and Items of Note:¶

All is well and dandy, the regions and organizations are dropped and we can now begin. Except, look above at Antigua and Barbuda. It appears they either did not have data at the time or did not yet exist. Eitherway, N/A values are not good and need to be delt with. To that end, there is no one good way to deal with the N/A values, and all options were debated over. The issue is mean, median, mode, etc. are out of the picture as it would skew the data, making them not usable in this case. Another option would be to drop the effected rows/columns, but that would also not be a option since it would effect the sizes of each row and would take away from analysis. For that reason, all problems below will be treated as statistics since 1970/1971 unless otherwise stated, and countries that do not have values since then will have a 0 in-place of the N/A. This is done with the fillna method of dataframes, with the argument 0 passed in as the value we want filled in. We will have to do this for both gdpValues and growthRates.

Question 1: What are the top 5 countries by GDP in 2023 and 2033?¶

In this problem, we will look at the Top 5 countries in terms of GDP Value in 2023 and then the prediced GDP Values of 2033.

Code Explanation and Items of Note:¶

Here we will make use of the info method, which returns every column and the type that it is. We will apply it to both gdpValues and GrowthRates. We will access the "Country" and "y2023"/"y2033" columns of the dataframe. We can think of this as projecting or displaying just these two columns of the entire dataset. We then use the sort_values() method, passing in y2023/y2033 arguments to the by= argument as to instruct the method to sort by the values of that column. We also pass in False for the ascending argument so we have the sorted values go from top to bottom. Then we will add the .head(5) method call to both code segments because we only want the top 5 and not the entire dataframe.

Key Notes Though it may seem misleading, the y2023 and y2033 column are not the years themselves, but the GDP values for each country in those years.

Question 2: When are India and China set to overtake traditonal powers such as Germany and the USA in GDP?¶

In this problem, we will look at when emerging powers such as China and India are set to overtake their closest "Rivals" (in our case rivals of GDP that we established above, though you could argue the USA and China are somewhat rivals, especially economic rivals) in GDP.

Code Explanation and Items of Note:¶

Here, both problems make use of very similar code with one to two minute difference. The first few lines of code are all for configuring the impending matplotlib figure so it is descriptive and adds value to the data that it is representing. First, we use the figure method, passing in 24/8 to figsize which sets the size of our figure. 24 represents length and 8 represents height. We then set the title, x, and y label of the graph respectively by using the title, xlabel, and ylabel methods respectively and pasing in the string we want displayed in. The next line of code, xticks with rotation being configured to 300 is a stylistic choice made out of neccessity. At-first, it was impossible to view the year labels and thus they were rotated to see them better.

As for the values in the plot it self, they are plotted using the plot function, and uses gdpValues.columns[1:] as the x-arguement. This line of code effectively brings out every year, with the [1:] being a specification of what values to use, 1 till the end, since 0 or the start is not a year and is a label, thus not good for graphing. The Y-Argument is (np.delete(gdpValues.loc[gdpValues["Country"] == "Country of Interest"].values, 0)) and it does a variety of things. Firstly, the np.delete function of numpy is used to delete the first value of the GDP values of the countries as it is a label and thus not graphable. The first argument in this function is the values itself, making use of loc to search within the gdpValues dataset for rows with the speficiation that it is rows in the dataset where the Country column is the country we want. In this case, thsoe being Germany, India, China, and the USA.

After ploting each country of interest, we use the plt.legend() method to add a key to the graph, with the names of what each line means being passed in as a list in order of how it was graphed. Finally we use plt.show to show the graph.

In [16]:
plt.figure(figsize = (24,8)) #Set Fig Size
plt.title("Germany vs. India") #Set Title
plt.xlabel("Year") #Set XLabel
plt.ylabel("GDP in Millions") #Set YLabel
plt.xticks(rotation = 300) #Set Rotations
plt.plot(gdpValues.columns[1:], np.delete(gdpValues.loc[gdpValues["Country"] == "Germany"].values, 0)) #Graph Germany
plt.plot(gdpValues.columns[1:], np.delete(gdpValues.loc[gdpValues["Country"] == "India"].values, 0)) #Graph India
plt.legend(['Germany', 'India']) #Set Legend
plt.show() #Show Graph

Key Takeaways:¶

Germany has been a fairly consistent power in-terms of growth and has seen an increase of GDP over-time. That being said, India has seen unprecedented growth since since the start of 2000 and has seen a much sharper rate of increase, and it is currently predicted to overtake Germany by 2026. This doubles down on the trends we saw above where Germany only say minute gains in GDP value over the 10 year predicted period where as India saw an almost doubled GDP, which is supported by the sheer rate of increase in GDP value.

Question 3: What are the top 5 and lowest 5 country GDPs each year from 1970 - 2033?¶

In this problem, we are interested in building on-top of the themes from the problems above and try and find the countryes that were the Top5

Code Explanation and Items of Note:¶

Here, first we create a list called yearList which contains every year, using the argument from above to extract the years which are the column names from 1 to the end (with 0 being a label), ahd this time we conver it to a numpy array. We also create a empty list called top5List.

After that, we are using a loop that for each year element that is in yearList from 0 to the end of the list, it will go in and store in a variable called currentTop5 the top 5 countries for that year. This is done in a very similar way to how we did it in problem 1, minus this time, instead of passing in a specific year, we go year by year by incrementing up the yearList and storing the .head(5) or top 5 for that year in this variable.

After this, we append the top5 for each year in the afformentioned top5 list by appending in a nested list or a list inside of a list. For each nested list, we take the year (using the replace method to take the string and remove the y from it*, and the extracted top 5 countries from the head function, with the country column of each head function being extracted, converted to a numpy array, and then having the top 5 extracted manually 1-5 through list comprehension.

After the loop terminates, we create a new dataframe called top5DF and use the pd.DataFrame method with the list passed in to conver it to a dataframe for much more cleaner displaying, also using the transpose method of dataframes to have it neatly print side by side year after year.

Key Findings:¶

I found it very interesting to see how much difference time can make when it comes to the rapidly changing economies of our world. Although the United States is consistently on top until our predicted timefrine established above, the United Kingdom and France used to be on the list, and Japan and Germany were 2 and three respectively. Then in our modern era Japan and Germany are knocked down by China and the United Kingdom and France are no where to be seen with India now being number 5.

It is definetly very interesting to view these trends and see how things shape up over-time in the coming years and decades.

In [18]:
yearList = gdpValues.columns[1:].to_numpy()
top5List = []
for i in range(len(yearList)):
    currentTop5 = gdpValues[["Country", yearList[i]]].sort_values(by=yearList[i], ascending=False).head(5)
    top5List.append([yearList[i].replace('y', ''), currentTop5["Country"].to_numpy()[0], currentTop5["Country"].to_numpy()[1], currentTop5["Country"].to_numpy()[2], currentTop5["Country"].to_numpy()[3], currentTop5["Country"].to_numpy()[4]])
top5DF = pd.DataFrame(top5List).transpose()
top5DF

Question 4: What are the Highest and Lowest Changes in GDP from 1970 to 2033¶

In this problem, we are interested in seeing the countries that have had the highest and lowest changes in GDP during the course of the data colletion period.

Code Explanation and Items of Note:¶

Like the previous problem, this problem starts by extracting a certain column from the dataframe and converting it to a numpy array. This time, we make use of the country column. After that, we make use of the ability of dataframes and Numpy Arrays to handle vector mathamatics and diretly subtract all values for every country between 2023 and 2000, converting the difference to numpy. After that, we join the list of countries with the list in difference of GDP for each country, conver it to a dataframe, sort it (with 1 refering to the values present) and printing out the head and tail (which print out the top and bottom 5).

Key Takeaways:¶

It is very interesting to see the scale of which China had played catch up since the start of the data collection period, a much expected catchup considering it will cross the United States in GDP, but still one that is very unprecented. China has seen double the increase in GDP then the US has seen in the same period while simultenously starting in a much lower place. India has also made major gains in the period, though not in the scale scale as the United States and China, though it is still much larger compared to the next closer countries that have made gains: Korea and the United Kingdom.

As for the Bottom 5, it was very interesting to see that other then Tonga (which made almost neglible changes in GDP in the past 50 years) every other country (baring Peurto Rico which is a teritory though is still interesting to note the extent to which it has seen some decline) has seen decline, with Venezuela seeing a fairly large decline in GDP compared to the next-nearest Yemen. If you were interested in a reading on what happened to Venezuela, Here is a Interesting Article.

Question 8: What are the Top and Bottom 5 in Growth Rate?¶

Back to more traditional questions, this question aims to see what the Top and Bottom 5 countries were in Growth Rate. This is accomplished by taking the mean of each countries growth rate from the start. You may wonder, why mean? I choose mean as a indicator for this problem because I feel it is best equiped to show a countries average growth rate since the start rather then other stastical functions which may have been swayed by bad years or years of major growth. Mean is also effected by these, but it also takes into account the normal years where nothing of note is neccesarily happening.

Code Explanation and Items of Note:¶

Firstly, I extract the the years of the growthList dataset and I export it to a numpy array. I also extract the list of all all country names, specifically its values, and store it in a list. I then iterate over the length of the length of a list of values of the country column to iterate over each county where I go and calculate the mean for each country, using previous techniques of list comprehension to overcome issues sorrounding the labels present in the data. I then apped the name of the country and the mean growth rate in a nested list like previous problems, converting it to a DataFrame and then sorting the values (as a refresher by column 1 which is the values) and then printing the head and tail.

Key Takeaways:¶

It was very interesting to see that, when it was all said in done, the countries of Laos and Guinea actually had the highest growth even though you may not have considered them to be on this list as their GDPs were very small. It is also interesting to see Botswana and Iraq on the list for the same reason. Finally it is suprising to see China as only third after discusing its unparalled growth previously, though this is likely due to the fact that up until th 2000s China's Economy was not yet ramping up at the speed it had post 2000, and thus its mean growth rate is brought done by those days. Other then that, I see nothing too unebleivable in the bottom 5 growth rate, minus the fact that Venezuala managed to hang on to a barely positive mean growth rate even though its GDP had fallen so much compared to where it started, pointing to major economic fluctuation as a possible explanation.

Well as I had explained when we first started the project and I had used the describe function, it is interesting because it is able to see how much variance there is in the GDPs of the world compared to the mean GDP, aka is there a gdp gap between the countries of the world.
